11 12.12 14.10 14.94 21.72 16.82\n[145] 12.61 13.40 12.64 12.24  9.13 12.31 19.68 19.83 15.34 15.61 14.07 13.64\n[157] 16.87 11.89 12.92 19.93 23.72 23.13 13.35 11.51 18.51 17.24 11.92 12.36\n[169] 13.42 11.45 11.09 14.19 14.22 12.15 10.49 11.29 11.74  9.53  7.65  7.21\n[181]  7.56  8.14 11.07 16.93 11.12  8.79 16.03 18.87 17.72 14.72 14.08 14.21\n[193]  9.99  6.63 10.11 12.64 15.06 14.21 14.20 16.39 16.31 16.07 17.83 20.24\n[205] 14.28 17.10 17.00 18.88 17.13 23.68 24.72 19.74 24.12 33.57\n```\n\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\nThis function generalizes the original script by accepting a user-supplied vector of PDB IDs, instead of hard-coding 4AKE, 1AKE, and 1E4Y, and using a loop to apply the same workflow, which is to read the structure, subset to the chosen chain and atom type, and then extract B-factors for any number of input proteins. It then produces the requested B-factor plot for a specific structure chosen via plot_id and returns the B-factor vectors for all inputs, making the analysis reusable and avoiding repeated copy/paste code.\n",
